'l'lt V. The points wherein usus differed from usufruct are clearly pointed out in §§1-4. The commonest mode in which the right was created was testament, and upon the principle ‘in testamentis plenius voluntates testantium interpretamur' the powers of the usuary were then sometimes enlarged beyond their normal compass in order to give effect to the bequest: e. g. if the usus were bequeathed of a wood so distant that it would not pay the legatee to go and fetcli the timber for personat consumption, he might sell it, Dig. 7. 8. 22. pr. On the same principle the legatee of the usus of a house might let such part of it as he did not require for himself and his family, Dig. ib. 2. 1, but not the whole: though the general rule was that a usuary could not transfer even the enjoyment of his right or any part of it, for to let another use a thing is not to use it oneself, and to do so for a merces is practically fructus.
